Former health minister, Zweli Mkhize is among the guests honouring a fallen member of AmaZulu regiments, Amabutho. This is his second public event in the past two weeks. Earlier this month religious and traditional leaders led a prayer service for the former ANC NEC member and his family. eNCA's Lethiwe Mdluli is covering this story. Courtesy #DStv403 KWANYAVU - Another group comes out to support former Health minister, Zweli Mkhize, for the ANC and eventually, South African presidency position. AmaZulu regiments, better known as Amabutho, say they’d like Mkhize to raise his hand. WATCH: Mkhize Prayer | Prayers for embattled former minister They’re the second group to lend support after religious and traditional leaders held a prayer service for Mkhize and his family two weeks ago. Amabutho's KwaZulu-Natal provincial leader, Simon Ngubane, says they'll be happy if Mkhize is elected at the upcoming ANC national conference but the AmaZulu regiments have no influence or role in ANC politics or elections. READ: Mkhize wants SIU report into Digital Vibes saga set aside On Sunday Mkhize was among guests honouring a fallen Amabutho member, Khuliphi Ndimande. Ngubane said, "we would be very happy if Zweli Mkhize were to be President of this country, because he knows the needs of Amabutho. He has done plenty for us, but we not only want him to do good for us but for the rest of the country." "We know very well that he is an empathetic man, he was born with such a gift. We would be very happy if Zweli Mkhize were to become president of the country."